title: For Sale:  Tactical Folder Czeck VZ2008 The NON-AK AK Lighter/Better 3 Mags/Sling/Grip More
postcontent: PERFECT Condition-- MANY MORE PHOTOS AVAILABLEHas had 200 rounds through it, not that it matters. A folding stock, lightweight Czeck rifle that looks like an AK, fires the same ammo as an AK, even sounds like an AK, BUT...completely different striker firing system with no hammer. Milled receiver, yet it is 1 pound lighter than a stamped AK. The standard Czeck rifle, the VZ58, first issued in 1958, comes with what is affectionately known as "beaver barf" furniture. A shortage of wood, combined with the superior properties of plastics led to tossing wood in a shredder and mixing it with plastic. That way any pieces of wood and even scraps could be used and large solid pieces were not needed. It is also much more efficient to change shapes. This folding rifle has had the "beaver barf" handguards removed, and a Mako slim railed front end installed. It has a top and bottom rail, and a forward grip looks great (get the folding one). As the grip was the standard AK shape, or just a rectangular slab, I replaced it with the finest ergo grip of all my military rifles from FAB DEFENSE. It feels great to hold. They make this $12 piece of plastic that slips over the buttstock with a dimpled rear surface. It extends the length just a tad but more important, it will not slide off your shirt as the bare metal does. It has enough "grip" to stay in place now. A black sling is added and you are left with a compact 26.5 inch package. Just over the legal minimum. It has the standard AK style slant muzzle-brake but you can easily add many others in under a minute. They sell an M16 style bird cage for $10 that screws right on and looks better. They just had a bunch of these come in and many have a plastic railed front end added. Atlantic Firearms and other places have them for $699 plus shipping with ONLY 1 mag, NO FAB Defense ergo-grip, no sling and no stock stippled panel. You are looking at $735 delivered PLUS what the FFL charges and then add $40 or more for 2 more mags and $25 for the grip and $12 for the sling plus $12 for that piece of plastic on the stock (makes a big difference). About $842 to get this same package in your hands. Or, $665 and it is yours! Below is the description from Century who makes them. Due to the import laws, the receiver and barrel are made in the USA, machined for a bar of steel, and then an original Czeck parts kit is installed. Local sales FTF with proper ID and if you are not local, I will ship to your FFL for $36THIS IS THE INFO ON THE RIFLE SOLD BY ATLANTIC--The rifle I am selling has 3 mags, sling, stock pad, Mako railed front end and ergo grip by FAB DEFENSECentury International Arms VZ2008 7.62x39 caliber semi-automatic Rifle. Originally issued to the Czech army in 1958, the VZ58 is still in use by both the Czech and Slovak armies, their police and customs agents. Though similar to the other rifles of this style in appearance, the VZ58 uses a completely different bolt and fire control system. Even with a machined receiver, the VZ2008 is lighter than most similarly styled firearms with a sheet metal receiver. Features a U.S. made receiver machined out of a bar of premium steel and a quality U.S. made barrel. All metal parts are bead blasted and coated with a non reflective finish. title: For Sale:  1840 Springer O/U Rifle-Shotgun Combo
postcontent: You are bidding on a very old and rare J. Springer over-under percussion rifle and shotgun combo. One set of barrels feature a .50-caliber rifle barrel atop a shotgun barrel. The other set is two shotgun barrels. In World War I, a British Lt. Col. Townsley moved the Lee Firearms Collection from London to Vancouver, Canada. The father of the set's current owner me Townsley there and acquired the Springer from him in 1941. Springer made the package in about 1840, and it's well preserved with elaborate engraving, beautiful stock work and Springer's name inlaid in gold atop both sets of barrels. This was a unique arm to begin with and even a more rare and desirable collectible now. Don't let it get away. Buyer pays actual shipping.

title: For Sale:  WW2 German Nazi Feg G98/40 8mm Mauser Rifle jhv 41
postcontent: a superb addition to the museum or dedicated private collection. Scarce, early-war jhv-code G98/40 rifle...this G98/40 was produced in 1941 by Hungarian icon Feg(Femaru). An upgrade of the Model 35 Mannlicher design, the G98/40 was modified to German requirements, which included bending the bolt handle, the addition of a Mauser-style staggered-column box magazine, K98k-style forestock/bayonet fixture, and rechambering for 7.92x57mm Mauser. Manufactured at Feg(and possibly Danuvia) for only four years beginning in 1940, production of this excellent rifle totalled just 130,000. Highly-regarded by the Germans, a number were lost to the war on the Eastern Front and this K98k-substitute weapon is regarded by collectors as uncommon at best. In original, non-import marked condition, this weapon was presumably brought back to the states by a veteran returning from the war. Composed of all-matching components, with the exception of the safety and bolt head, this fine G98/40 would be .
